There are four kinds of it z one with {2²} me ἰωὴ· fatter leaves than those of coriander and nearly as broad as those of mallows‚ of a leaden colour, with a tall, graceful stem and a whitish root. It grows on moist and shaded cross-paths. The second is more leafy, with more indentations in the leaves, and with taller stems. The third is the smallest, with a strong smell and a golden flower. The fourth is like it, but the flower is of the colour of milk. All have a caustic property3 if leaves are applied raw, they raise blisters as does fire. Accordingly they are used for leprous sores and itch, and to remove scars on the skin3 they are ingredients of all caustic preparations. They are applied to mange, but are removed quickly. The root if chewed up for tooth- ache too long breaks off the teeth‚ and the dried root chopped fine makes a snuff.
